{"title_page": "James Daniel Gardner", "text_new": "{{Infobox military person\n|name=James Daniel Gardner\n|birth_date= {{Birth date|1839|9|16}}\n|death_date= {{Death date and age|1905|9|29|1839|9|16}}\n|birth_place=[[Gloucester, Virginia|Gloucester]], [[Virginia]]\n|death_place=[[Clarks Summit, Pennsylvania|Clarks Summit]], [[Pennsylvania]]\n|placeofburial= Calvary Crest Cemetery, [[Ottumwa, Iowa]]\n|placeofburial_label= Place of burial\n|image= James Daniel Gardner.jpg\n|caption=Sergeant James D. Gardner\n|nickname=\n|allegiance= {{flag|United States of America}}<br/>[[Union (American Civil War)|Union]]\n|branch= {{flag|United States Army}}<br/>[[Union Army]]\n|serviceyears=1863\u20131866\n|rank=[[File:Union Army Infantry Sergeant.png|25 px]] [[Sergeant#United States|Sergeant]]\n|commands=\n|unit={{flagicon|United States|1863}} [[36th United States Colored Infantry|36th Regiment United States Colored Troops]]\n|battles=[[American Civil War]]<br/>{{*}} [[Battle of Chaffin's Farm]]\n|awards=[[File:Medal of Honor ribbon.svg|30 px]] [[Medal of Honor]]\n|laterwork=\n}}\n'''James Daniel Gardner''', also spelled as '''Gardiner''' (September 16, 1839 &ndash; September 29, 1905), was an [[African American]] [[Union Army]] soldier during the [[American Civil War]] and a recipient of the United States military's highest decoration, the [[Medal of Honor]], for his actions at the [[Battle of Chaffin's Farm]].\n\n==Biography==\nGardner was born on September 16, 1839, in [[Gloucester, Virginia]]. He worked as an [[oyster]]man before enlisting in the [[Union Army]] from [[Yorktown, Virginia]], on September 15, 1863. He joined Company I of the [[36th United States Colored Infantry|36th Regiment United States Colored Troops Troops]] as a [[private (rank)|private]]. His enlistment papers recorded his surname as \"Gardiner.\"<ref name=\"Hanna\">Hanna, pp 33\u201335</ref>\n\nAt the Battle of Chaffin's Farm, Virginia, on September 29, 1864, Gardner's regiment was among a [[Division (military)|division]] of black troops assigned to attack the [[Confederate States of America|Confederate]] defenses at New Market Heights. The defenses consisted of two lines of [[abatis]] and one line of [[palisade]]s manned by Brigadier General [[John Gregg (CSA)|John Gregg]]'s [[Texas Brigade]]. The attack was met with intense Confederate fire; over fifty percent of the black troops were killed, captured, or wounded.<ref name=\"Hanna\"/> During the assault, Gardner advanced ahead of his unit into the Confederate fortifications, \"shot a rebel officer who was on the parapet rallying his men, and then ran him through with his bayonet.\"<ref name=\"citation\">{{Cite web |title=Civil War Medal of Honor recipients (A\u2013L) |work=Medal of Honor citations |publisher=[[United States Army Center of Military History]] |date=January 27, 2009 |url=http://www.history.army.mil/html/moh/civwaral.html |accessdate=2009-02-13}}</ref>\nThe day after the battle, Gardner was promoted to [[Sergeant#United States|sergeant]].<ref name=\"Hanna\"/> Several months later and three days before the end of the war, on April 6, 1865, he was issued the Medal of Honor for his actions at Chaffin's Farm.<ref name=\"citation\"/>\n\nAfter the war, Gardner moved with his regiment westward to the [[Texas]] frontier, where his service was marred by disciplinary problems. He was reduced in rank to private on July 13, 1865, and was placed in confinement in [[Brazos Santiago]] on March 29, 1866. He was mustered out of the Army in Brazos Santiago on September 20, 1866, after three years of service.<ref name=\"Hanna\"/>\n\nHe died in [[Clarks Summit, Pennsylvania]], on September 29, 1905, the 41st anniversary of his Medal of Honor action. Aged 66 at his death, Gardner was buried at Calvary Crest Cemetery in [[Ottumwa, Iowa]].<ref name=\"Hanna\"/> A memorial commemorating Gardner, erected in 2005, and unveiled in 2006, was placed in his hometown of Gloucester, Virginia.<ref>{{Cite web|publisher=Gloucester County, Virginia |title=Civil War Monument (Private James Daniel Gardner) |date=May 9, 2008 |url=http://www.gloucesterva.info/MONU2.HTM |accessdate=2009-02-13 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080516195016/http://www.gloucesterva.info/MONU2.HTM |archivedate=May 16, 2008 }}</ref>\n\n==Medal of Honor citation==\nRank and organization: Private, Company I, 36th U.S. Colored Troops. Place and date: At Chapins Farm, Va., September 29, 1864. Entered service at:Yorktown, Virginia. Birth: Gloucester, Va. Date of issue: April 6, 1865.<ref name=\"citation\"/>\n\nCitation:\n\n<blockquote>Rushed in advance of his brigade, shot a rebel officer who was on the parapet rallying his men, and then ran him through with his bayonet.<ref name=\"citation\"/></blockquote>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Biography|American Civil War|United States}}\n\n*[[List of American Civil War Medal of Honor recipients: G\u2013L#G|List of American Civil War Medal of Honor recipients: G\u2013L]]\n*[[List of African American Medal of Honor recipients]]\n*Melvin Claxton and Mark Puls, ''Uncommon valor : a story of race, patriotism, and glory in the final battles of the Civil War'', (Wiley, 2006) ({{ISBN|0471468231}})\n\n==References==\n:{{ACMH}}\n;Specific\n{{Reflist}}\n\n;General\n*{{Cite book\n  |last = Hanna\n  |first = Charles W.\n  |title = African American recipients of the Medal of Honor: a biographical dictionary, Civil War through Vietnam War\n  |publisher = McFarland & Company, Inc., Publishers\n  |year = 2002\n  |location = Jefferson, North Carolina\n  |pages = 33\u201335\n  |isbn = 0-7864-1355-7}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Find a Grave|7661519|work=Claim to Fame: Medal of Honor recipients|accessdate=2009-03-15}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gardner, James Daniel}}\n[[Category:1839 births]]\n[[Category:1905 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Gloucester Courthouse, Virginia]]\n[[Category:People of Virginia in the American Civil War]]\n[[Category:African Americans in the American Civil War]]\n[[Category:Union Army soldiers]]\n[[Category:United States Army Medal of Honor recipients]]\n[[Category:American Civil War recipients of the Medal of Honor]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox military person\n|name=James Daniel Gardner\n|birth_date= {{Birth date|1839|9|16}}\n|death_date= {{Death date and age|1905|9|29|1839|9|16}}\n|birth_place=[[Gloucester, Virginia|Gloucester]], [[Virginia]]\n|death_place=[[Clarks Summit, Pennsylvania|Clarks Summit]], [[Pennsylvania]]\n|placeofburial= Calvary Crest Cemetery, [[Ottumwa, Iowa]]\n|placeofburial_label= Place of burial\n|image= James Daniel Gardner.jpg\n|caption=Sergeant James D. Gardner\n|nickname=\n|allegiance= {{flag|United States of America}}<br/>[[Union (American Civil War)|Union]]\n|branch= {{flag|United States Army}}<br/>[[Union Army]]\n|serviceyears=1863\u20131866\n|rank=[[File:Union Army Infantry Sergeant.png|25 px]] [[Sergeant#United States|Sergeant]]\n|commands=\n|unit=[[36th United States Colored Infantry|36th Regiment United States Colored Troops]]\n|battles=[[American Civil War]]<br/>{{*}} [[Battle of Chaffin's Farm]]\n|awards=[[File:Medal of Honor ribbon.svg|30 px]] [[Medal of Honor]]\n|laterwork=\n}}\n'''James Daniel Gardner''', also spelled as '''Gardiner''' (September 16, 1839 &ndash; September 29, 1905), was an [[African American]] [[Union Army]] soldier during the [[American Civil War]] and a recipient of the United States military's highest decoration, the [[Medal of Honor]], for his actions at the [[Battle of Chaffin's Farm]].\n\n==Biography==\nGardner was born on September 16, 1839, in [[Gloucester, Virginia]]. He worked as an [[oyster]]man before enlisting in the [[Union Army]] from [[Yorktown, Virginia]], on September 15, 1863. He joined Company I of the [[36th United States Colored Infantry|36th Regiment United States Colored Troops Troops]] as a [[private (rank)|private]]. His enlistment papers recorded his surname as \"Gardiner.\"<ref name=\"Hanna\">Hanna, pp 33\u201335</ref>\n\nAt the Battle of Chaffin's Farm, Virginia, on September 29, 1864, Gardner's regiment was among a [[Division (military)|division]] of black troops assigned to attack the [[Confederate States of America|Confederate]] defenses at New Market Heights. The defenses consisted of two lines of [[abatis]] and one line of [[palisade]]s manned by Brigadier General [[John Gregg (CSA)|John Gregg]]'s [[Texas Brigade]]. The attack was met with intense Confederate fire; over fifty percent of the black troops were killed, captured, or wounded.<ref name=\"Hanna\"/> During the assault, Gardner advanced ahead of his unit into the Confederate fortifications, \"shot a rebel officer who was on the parapet rallying his men, and then ran him through with his bayonet.\"<ref name=\"citation\">{{Cite web |title=Civil War Medal of Honor recipients (A\u2013L) |work=Medal of Honor citations |publisher=[[United States Army Center of Military History]] |date=January 27, 2009 |url=http://www.history.army.mil/html/moh/civwaral.html |accessdate=2009-02-13}}</ref>\nThe day after the battle, Gardner was promoted to [[Sergeant#United States|sergeant]].<ref name=\"Hanna\"/> Several months later and three days before the end of the war, on April 6, 1865, he was issued the Medal of Honor for his actions at Chaffin's Farm.<ref name=\"citation\"/>\n\nAfter the war, Gardner moved with his regiment westward to the [[Texas]] frontier, where his service was marred by disciplinary problems. He was reduced in rank to private on July 13, 1865, and was placed in confinement in [[Brazos Santiago]] on March 29, 1866. He was mustered out of the Army in Brazos Santiago on September 20, 1866, after three years of service.<ref name=\"Hanna\"/>\n\nHe died in [[Clarks Summit, Pennsylvania]], on September 29, 1905, the 41st anniversary of his Medal of Honor action. Aged 66 at his death, Gardner was buried at Calvary Crest Cemetery in [[Ottumwa, Iowa]].<ref name=\"Hanna\"/> A memorial commemorating Gardner, erected in 2005, and unveiled in 2006, was placed in his hometown of Gloucester, Virginia.<ref>{{Cite web|publisher=Gloucester County, Virginia |title=Civil War Monument (Private James Daniel Gardner) |date=May 9, 2008 |url=http://www.gloucesterva.info/MONU2.HTM |accessdate=2009-02-13 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080516195016/http://www.gloucesterva.info/MONU2.HTM |archivedate=May 16, 2008 }}</ref>\n\n==Medal of Honor citation==\nRank and organization: Private, Company I, 36th U.S. Colored Troops. Place and date: At Chapins Farm, Va., September 29, 1864. Entered service at:Yorktown, Virginia. Birth: Gloucester, Va. Date of issue: April 6, 1865.<ref name=\"citation\"/>\n\nCitation:\n\n<blockquote>Rushed in advance of his brigade, shot a rebel officer who was on the parapet rallying his men, and then ran him through with his bayonet.<ref name=\"citation\"/></blockquote>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Biography|American Civil War|United States}}\n\n*[[List of American Civil War Medal of Honor recipients: G\u2013L#G|List of American Civil War Medal of Honor recipients: G\u2013L]]\n*[[List of African American Medal of Honor recipients]]\n*Melvin Claxton and Mark Puls, ''Uncommon valor : a story of race, patriotism, and glory in the final battles of the Civil War'', (Wiley, 2006) ({{ISBN|0471468231}})\n\n==References==\n:{{ACMH}}\n;Specific\n{{Reflist}}\n\n;General\n*{{Cite book\n  |last = Hanna\n  |first = Charles W.\n  |title = African American recipients of the Medal of Honor: a biographical dictionary, Civil War through Vietnam War\n  |publisher = McFarland & Company, Inc., Publishers\n  |year = 2002\n  |location = Jefferson, North Carolina\n  |pages = 33\u201335\n  |isbn = 0-7864-1355-7}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Find a Grave|7661519|work=Claim to Fame: Medal of Honor recipients|accessdate=2009-03-15}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gardner, James Daniel}}\n[[Category:1839 births]]\n[[Category:1905 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Gloucester Courthouse, Virginia]]\n[[Category:People of Virginia in